To find the x-intercepts, we substitute y=\alert{0} into the original equation to obtain \begin{aligned}[t] 4x^2 + 9(\alert{0})^2 - 16x - 18 (\alert{0}) - 11 \amp = 0\\ 4x^2 - 16x - 11 \amp = 0\\ \end{aligned}
We use the quadratic formula to solve for x.
x = \dfrac{16 \pm \sqrt{432}}{8} = 2 \pm \dfrac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}
The x-intercepts are ( 2 \pm \dfrac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}, 0), or approximately (4.6,0) and (-0.6,0). To find the y-intercepts, we substitute x=\alert{0} into the given equation to obtain \begin{aligned}[t] 4(\alert{0})^2 + 9y^2 - 16(\alert{0}) - 18y - 11 \amp = 0\\ 9y^2 - 18y - 11 \amp = 0\\ \end{aligned}
We use the quadratic formula to solve for y.
y = \dfrac{18 \pm \sqrt{720}}{18} = 1 \pm \dfrac{2\sqrt{5}}{3}
The y-intercepts are (0, 1 \pm \dfrac{2\sqrt{5}}{3}), or approximately (0, 2.5) and (0,-0.5).

The graph is a hyperbola with center at (-1,-2). Because the y^2-term is positive, the transverse axis is parallel to the y-axis, and
        b^2 = 9,~~a^2 = \dfrac{9}{4}

    Thus, b=3 and a = \dfrac{3}{2}, and the vertices are (-1,1) and (-1,5). The ends of the conjugate axis are (\dfrac{-5}{2}, -2) and (\dfrac{1}{2}, -2).
